      "Lean's coercion rules, `x` is also considered to be in the support of `$[0..n]`.\n\nHowever, the actual formal proof will depend on Lean's implementation of coercions and how it treats the support in the presence of coercions. \n\n### Step-by-Step Abstract Plan\n\n1. Understand how Lean coerces `ZMod (n + 1)` to `Fin (n + 1)` and uses this coercion in the context of support.\n2. Recognize that the support of `$[0..n]` is all of `Fin (n + 1)` because it is uniform.\n3. Show that any `x : ZMod (n + 1)` can be mapped to `Fin (n + 1)` via coercion, and thus is in the support.\n\nBut perhaps it is simpler:\n1. The support of `$[0..n]` is all of `Fin (n + 1)` because it is a uniform distribution.\n2. For any `x : ZMod (n + 1)`, there is a corresponding element in `Fin (n + 1)` (its canonical representative).\n3. Therefore, `x` is in the support of `$[0..n]` via this correspondence.\n\nBut perhaps we can",
